        "issue": "No circuit breaker on OrderService. If OrderService degrades, CartService has no protection — every checkout attempt will hang for up to 5s before failing, exhausting connection pools and cascading failure upstream."
      },
      {
        "from": "CartService",
        "to": "PaymentService",
        "status": "risk",
        "issue": "Circuit breaker exists (good), but PaymentService's external gateway has an 8s timeout while CartService only allows 5s. CartService will timeout and treat the call as failed even when the payment gateway is still processing. This creates a critical consistency gap: payment may succeed at the gateway but CartService records it as failed."
      },
      {
        "from": "OrderService",
        "to": "InventoryService",
        "status": "risk",
        "issue": "Retry on timeout means worst-case latency is 6s (3s + 3s), but CartService only allows 5s for the OrderService call. A single InventoryService timeout + retry will breach CartService's deadline, causing CartService to abandon the request while OrderService is still retrying — potentially reserving stock for an order CartService considers failed."
      },
      {
        "from": "PaymentService",
        "to": "External Payment Gateway",
        "status": "risk",
        "issue": "No circuit breaker on the external payment gateway. If the gateway degrades (responds slowly but within 8s), every payment request queues up, PaymentService threads/connections saturate, and the entire checkout flow backs up. This is the highest-entropy external dependency with zero protection."
      }
    ],
    "contract_compliance": "Timeout contracts are misaligned across the call chain. CartService (5s) < OrderService retry window (6s) and CartService (5s) < PaymentService gateway timeout (8s). Both downstream services can outlive their caller's patience, creating orphaned operations.",
    "data_flow_integrity": "Critical gap: CartService calls OrderService then PaymentService synchronously with no compensation. If OrderService succeeds (order created, stock reserved) but PaymentService fails, there is no rollback of the order or stock reservation. This will leak reserved inventory on every payment failure."
  },

  "observability_review": {
    "logging": {
      "coverage": "gaps",
      "gaps": [
        "No mention of correlation/request IDs across the three services — debugging a failed checkout requires manually correlating logs by timestamp",
        "No structured logging of timeout events, circuit breaker state transitions, or orphaned operation detection",
        "No logging of the gap between 'payment gateway accepted' and 'CartService timed out' scenarios"
      ]
    },
    "metrics": {
      "coverage": "gaps",
      "gaps": [
        "No latency histograms (p50/p95/p99) at each service boundary to detect timeout budget violations before they cascade",
        "No metric tracking orphaned orders (order created but payment never attempted or failed)",
        "No circuit breaker state metric on CartService-to-PaymentService",
        "No inventory reservation leak counter (reserved but never fulfilled or released)",
        "No payment gateway success/failure/timeout rate from PaymentService"
      ]
    },
    "tracing": {
      "coverage": "missing",
      "gaps": [
        "No distributed tracing described across CartService -> OrderService -> InventoryService and CartService -> PaymentService -> Gateway",
        "Without tracing, diagnosing which leg of the checkout timed out requires grepping logs across 4+ services"
      ]
    },
    "debugging_capability": "Poor. At 3am, an on-call engineer facing 'checkout failures spiking' has no way to quickly determine whether the root cause is InventoryService latency, payment gateway degradation, or timeout misalignment. They would need to manually correlate logs across services with no request ID or trace."
  },

